console.pulsetech.description.help: Prints a list of valid commands to the console screen, along with one-line descriptions. Good for a quick, less detailed reference
console.pulsetech.description.clear: Removes all prior lines from this console's history
console.pulsetech.description.stop: Clears the console's internal signal buffer, which prevents it from outputting any more bits
console.pulsetech.description.define:
Define a new macro for use in this console.

For example: 'define cool emit 1010 num 10' defines a macro named 'cool' which, when run, performs the command sequence 'emit 1010 num 10'.

The name can be any unbroken word that is not a predefined command.

In addition, using ? in a macro defines a parameter. Macros with parameters are used like commands: for instance, a macro 'a' defined with 'define a emit 10 num ?' could be used with 'a 123' to effectively run 'emit 10 num 123'
help.pulsetech.loop: Loop to a repeat keyword a specified number of times
console.pulsetech.description.loop:
Repeat all commands until the 'repeat' command is reached the specified number of times.

For example: 'loop 3 emit 1 repeat' would have the same effect as 'emit 1 emit 1 emit 1'
help.pulsetech.repeat: Defines the end of a loop (see 'loop')
console.pulsetech.description.repeat: See 'loop' for details. Does nothing if not preceded by 'loop'.
help.pulsetech.wait: Delay execution for a number of game ticks
console.pulsetech.description.wait: Delay execution for a number of game ticks
help.pulsetech.emit: Send a sequence of bits from the output
console.pulsetech.description.emit:
Enqueues a sequence of bits for output.

Bits are represented with the digits 1 and 0. Each will be output for a single Redstone Tick
help.pulsetech.num: Send an 8 bit signed integer from the output
console.pulsetech.description.num:
Enqueues a litte-endian signed 8 bit integer for output.

Valid numbers range from -128 to 127, inclusive
help.pulsetech.color: Send an RGB Hex color code from the output
console.pulsetech.description.color:
Enqueues an RGB hexadecimal color code for output. For example, 'color FF0000' would emit the color red.

Colors are sent as a sequence of three numbers
console.pulsetech.macro_name_taken_1: Macro could not be defined: name
console.pulsetech.no_loop_parameter: Can't repeat invalid number of times
console.pulsetech.repeat_outside_loop: Invalid repeat keyword not after loop
console.pulsetech.error_loop_not_process: Mod error! Loop or repeat not preprocessed. Report this to hyperlynx!
console.pulsetech.looping: Looping prior command; run 'stop' to halt
console.pulsetech.delay_multi_parameter_: Delay only supports a single parameter
protocol.pulsetech.description.controlle: Emit a pulse after Delay pulse-times
Emit Count pulses with Delay pulse-times between each
protocol.pulsetech.description.scanner/m:
Set the scan mode, which decides which entities are scanned

Valid modes:
0 - Any
1 - Monster
2 - Animal
3 - Adult Animal
4 - Child Animal
5 - Nonliving other than Item
6 - Item
7 - Player
protocol.pulsetech.description.scanner/c: Emit the number of matching entities within 16 blocks
protocol.pulsetech.description.scanner/f: Emit the X, Y, and Z offsets to the nearest matching entity, or (0, 0, 0) if there are none
protocol.pulsetech.description.scanner/c: Emit a pulse if any matching entities are within 16 blocks
protocol.pulsetech.description.screen/cl: Reset the background color to black
protocol.pulsetech.description.screen/re: Reset the pen color to white
protocol.pulsetech.description.screen/ma: Draw a pixel of the pen color at the given coordinates on the foreground. Each must be between [0, 14]
protocol.pulsetech.description.screen/bo: Draw a box of the pen color within the given coordinates on the foreground. Each must be between [0, 14]
protocol.pulsetech.description.screen/to: Toggle on or off the foreground layer. It is still possible to draw to the foreground while it is not visible
protocol.pulsetech.description.cannon/ta: Aim the cannon at the specified offset from itself
protocol.pulsetech.description.cannon/nu:
Adjusts the target of the cannon after each time it is fired.

The parameter is a sequence of 8 bits in format UDNESW##, with each part defined as follows:
U - Up
D - Down
N - North
E - East
S - South
W - West
## - Two digit unsigned number that specifies how far to nudge
protocol.pulsetech.description.cannon/fi:
Fires the cannon toward the stored target, breaking the block at that location.
If a non-zero nudge is defined, also moves the target by that nudge
protocol.pulsetech.description.orb/spawn: Manifests the Orb one block above the Projector.
protocol.pulsetech.description.orb/move_:
Commands the Orb to move by the specified X offset.
The Orb will move in a straight line regardless of obstacles

Commands the Orb to move by the specified Y offset.
The Orb will move in a straight line regardless of obstacles

Commands the Orb to move by the specified Z offset.
The Orb will move in a straight line regardless of obstacles

Commands the Orb to move to a specified location relative to the Projector.
The Orb will move in a straight line regardless of obstacles
protocol.pulsetech.description.orb/grab: Latches onto an entity nearby the Orb, or drops a currently held entity. The entity will be held above the Orb as it moves
protocol.pulsetech.description.orb/toggl: Turns on or off PEN MODE. In PEN MODE, the Orb will leave a trail of particles. If it is holding a stack of items, the Orb will drop those items along its path if it moves. If the Orb is holding a stack of blocks, it will place them along any path it moves
Turns on or off PROJECTILE MODE. In PROJECTILE MODE, the Orb will rupture on contact with any entity or block. Entities will take damage when hit
protocol.pulsetech.error_none_loaded_des: No protocol was defined for this block! Please check your datapacks, reinstall Pulsetech, or report this error to hyperlynx
pulsetech.screen_swapped: Swapped screen data with data cell
